 Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Keighley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from a place so named in Yorkshire. The placename derives from an Old English personal name <i>Cyhha</i> + Old English <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’.","Americanized form of German <b>Kiechle</b> (see   Kuechle  ) or <b>Kiechler</b> (see   Kuechler  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Keithley","meanings":["English (Durham and Yorkshire): variant of   Keighley  ."]},{"name":"Kuechle","meanings":["South German (<b>Küchle</b>): metonymic occupational name for a pastry cook, from <i>Küchle</i> ‘cookie, little cake’ (see   Kuchler   1)."]},{"name":"Keathley","meanings":["English: variant of   Keighley  ."]},{"name":"Keightley","meanings":["English: variant of   Keighley  .","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Gatlaoich</b>, see   Gately  ."]},{"name":"Keatley","meanings":["English (Warwickshire and Staffordshire): variant of   Keighley  ."]},{"name":"Keithly","meanings":["English: variant of   Keighley  ."]},{"name":"Keigley","meanings":["Altered form of English   Keighley  ."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Richard I de Keighley was born about 1150 as the son of Ralph I de Keighley. He had at least 2 sons. He died from 1150 to 1199, in Keighley, Yorkshire, England."},"et":{"abt 1150–1150-1199":"umbes 1150–1150 kuni 1199","1150–1199":"1150–1199","–1193":"–1193","–1198":"–1198","1180–1243":"1180–1243","–1199":"–1199","1150-1199":"1150 kuni 1199","1243":"1243","1199":"1199","abt 1150":"umbes 1150","1198":"1198","1150":"1150","1193":"1193","1180":"1180","Keighley, Yorkshire, England":"Keighley, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"abt 1150–1150-1199":"noin 1150–vuodesta 1150 vuoteen 1199","1150–1199":"1150–1199","–1193":"–1193","–1198":"–1198","1180–1243":"1180–1243","–1199":"–1199","1150-1199":"vuodesta 1150 vuoteen 1199","1243":"1243","1199":"1199","abt 1150":"noin 1150","1198":"1198","1150":"1150","1193":"1193","1180":"1180","Keighley, Yorkshire, England":"Keighley, Yorkshire, England"},"fr":{"abt 1150–1150-1199":"environ 1150–du 1150 au 1199","1150–1199":"1150–1199","–1193":"–1